# SSE Real-Time Bridge: RabbitMQ → Frontend

## Background

The backend has a fully functional RabbitMQ **Event Bus** (`eventBus.js`) with:
- `notifyHandler.js` — writes DB rows to `notifications` table on `record.submitted`, `record.approved`, `record.sent_back`
- `auditHandler.js` — writes tamper-evident revision rows on all `record.*` events
- A `notifications` REST module with `GET /notifications`, `GET /notifications/count`, `PATCH /:id/read`, `PATCH /read-all`

**The problem is twofold:**
1. The notifications REST router is **not registered** in `app.js` (no import/mount)
2. There is **no real-time push channel** — the frontend only polls manually or uses hardcoded dummy notifications in `DashboardLayout.jsx`

The frontend navbar (`PoliceNavbar.jsx`) receives `notifications` as a prop from `DashboardLayout`, which currently holds **two hardcoded static dummy entries**. The `DashboardPage.jsx` hits the wrong endpoint (`/api/v1/auth/notifications` instead of `/api/v1/notifications`).

## Proposed Approach: Server-Sent Events (SSE)

**Why SSE instead of WebSockets:**
- SSE is simpler and works over standard HTTP — no need for `ws` package or socket.io
- Works natively with CORS and auth headers
- Perfect for one-way push (server → browser) which is what we need for notification delivery
- RabbitMQ handler already writes to DB; SSE just needs to signal the browser to "refresh"

